  // WindPeakDetails — prose
  std_ec1w_det_vb_prose: 'The basic wind velocity v_b is defined in EN 1991-1-4 §4.2(2)P as a function of wind direction and time of year at 10 m above ground of terrain Category II. The value of v_b includes the effects of the directional factor c_dir and the seasonal factor c_season and is provided in the National Annex. In these calculations the basic wind velocity is taken as:',
  std_ec1w_det_z0_prose_pre: 'The roughness length z₀ and the minimum height z_min are specified in EN 1991-1-4 Table 4.1 as a function of the terrain category. For terrain category',
  std_ec1w_det_z0_prose_post: 'the corresponding values are:',
  std_ec1w_det_kr_prose_pre: 'The terrain factor k_r depending on the roughness length z₀ =',
  std_ec1w_det_kr_prose_post: 'm is calculated in accordance with EN 1991-1-4 equation (4.5):',
  std_ec1w_det_cr_prose_pre: 'The roughness factor c_r(z_e) at the reference height z_e accounts for the variability of the mean wind velocity at the site. It is calculated in accordance with EN 1991-1-4 equation (4.4). For the examined case z_e',
  std_ec1w_det_cr_prose_post: 'z_min:',
  std_ec1w_det_c0_prose: 'Where orography (e.g. hills, cliffs, escarpments) is significant, its effect on wind velocities should be taken into account using an orography factor c₀(z_e) different from 1.0, as specified in EN 1991-1-4 §4.3.3. The recommended procedure for calculating c₀(z_e) is described in EN 1991-1-4 Annex A.3.',
  std_ec1w_det_vm_prose: 'The mean wind velocity v_m(z_e) at reference height z_e depends on the terrain roughness, terrain orography and the basic wind velocity v_b. It is determined using EN 1991-1-4 equation (4.3):',
  std_ec1w_det_iv_prose_pre: 'The turbulence intensity I_v(z_e) at reference height z_e is defined as the standard deviation of the turbulence divided by the mean wind velocity. It is calculated in accordance with EN 1991-1-4 equation (4.7). For the examined case z_e',
  std_ec1w_det_qb_prose: 'The basic velocity pressure q_b is the pressure corresponding to the wind momentum determined at the basic wind velocity v_b. It is calculated according to the fundamental relation specified in EN 1991-1-4 §4.5(1):',
  std_ec1w_det_qp_prose: 'The peak velocity pressure q_p(z_e) at reference height z_e includes mean and short-term velocity fluctuations. It is determined according to EN 1991-1-4 equation (4.8):',
  std_ec1w_det_forces_prose: 'The wind actions on the structure (forces and pressures) depend on q_p(z_e) as follows.',
  std_ec1w_det_pressures_heading: 'Wind pressures on surfaces',
  std_ec1w_det_we_prose_pre: 'The wind pressure on surfaces is derived from q_p(z_e) =',
  std_ec1w_det_we_prose_post: 'kN/m² by application of the appropriate pressure coefficient, as specified in EN 1991-1-4 §5.2.',
  std_ec1w_det_external: 'For external surfaces the wind pressure w_e is:',
  std_ec1w_det_internal: 'For internal surfaces the wind pressure w_i is:',
  std_ec1w_det_total_force_heading: 'Total wind force on structure or structural element',
  std_ec1w_det_fw_prose: 'The overall wind force F_w on the total structure or a structural element is estimated by application of the appropriate force coefficient, as specified in EN 1991-1-4 §5.3:',
  // CalcStep notes
  std_ec1w_det_note_kr: 'The terrain factor kr depends solely on the roughness length z₀ for the chosen terrain category, normalised against the reference roughness length z₀,II = 0.05 m (Category II). It scales the logarithmic wind profile to the appropriate roughness class.',
  std_ec1w_det_note_cr: 'The roughness factor cr(z) describes the variability of mean wind velocity with height due to ground roughness. It is based on a logarithmic wind profile valid for z_min ≤ z ≤ 200 m.',
  std_ec1w_det_note_c0_flat: 'c₀ = 1.0 — flat terrain, no orography correction applied.',
  std_ec1w_det_according_to: 'According to:',
  std_ec1w_det_note_c0_site: 'site-specific orography correction applied per EN 1991-1-4 §4.3.3.',
  std_ec1w_det_note_vm: 'The mean wind velocity vm(ze) is the 10-minute mean at height ze. The orography factor c₀ accounts for speed-up over hills. On flat terrain c₀ = 1.0.',
  std_ec1w_det_note_iv: 'kI = 1.0 is the turbulence factor (recommended value per EN 1991-1-4 §4.4). Higher turbulence intensity — rougher terrain or lower height — increases the gust factor (1 + 7·Iv) and therefore increases qp.',
  std_ec1w_det_note_qb: 'The basic velocity pressure qb is a reference value used to understand the energy content of the wind. Note that by definition 1 N = 1 kg·m/s². The design pressure qp(ze) is higher than qb because it includes the gust factor.',
